Perfect! Now let me compile a comprehensive guide with concrete code examples for your use case.

## Summary

I've researched Clerk's authentication component customization system. Here's a comprehensive guide to matching Clerk components to your black/white/zinc design system with sharp corners.

## Detailed Findings

### 1. ClerkProvider Appearance Prop Structure

**Source**: [Clerk Appearance Prop Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/overview)

**Relevance**: The `appearance` prop is the main customization interface. It can be applied globally to `<ClerkProvider>` or to individual components like `<SignIn />` and `<SignUp />`.

**Key Structure**:
```tsx
<ClerkProvider
  appearance={{
    baseTheme: undefined,     // Optional preset theme
    variables: {},            // General styles (colors, fonts, spacing)
    elements: {},             // Fine-grained element styling
    layout: {}                // Logo, terms links, etc.
  }}
>
  {children}
</ClerkProvider>
```

### 2. Available CSS Variables for Your Design System

**Source**: [Clerk Variables Prop Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/variables)

**Relevance**: These variables control the core visual properties that define your brand identity.

**Complete Variable List for Black/White/Zinc Theme**:

```tsx
import { ClerkProvider } from '@clerk/nextjs'

export default function RootLayout({ children }) {
  return (
    <ClerkProvider
      appearance={{
        variables: {
          // Colors - Black/White/Zinc palette
          colorPrimary: '#000000',              // Primary actions (black)
          colorForeground: '#000000',           // Primary text (black)
          colorBackground: '#ffffff',           // Card background (white)
          colorNeutral: '#71717a',              // Zinc-500 for neutral elements
          colorMutedForeground: '#a1a1aa',      // Zinc-400 for muted text

          // Input fields
          colorInputBackground: '#ffffff',      // White input backgrounds
          colorInputForeground: '#000000',      // Black input text

          // State colors (can use your accent palette)
          colorDanger: '#f43f5e',               // Rose for errors
          colorSuccess: '#10b981',              // Emerald for success
          colorWarning: '#f59e0b',              // Amber for warnings

          // Typography
          fontFamily: 'Switzer, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, sans-serif',
          fontSize: '0.875rem',                 // 14px base
          fontWeight: {
            normal: 400,
            medium: 500,
            semibold: 600,
            bold: 700,
          },

          // Sharp corners - CRITICAL for your design
          borderRadius: '0px',                  // NO border radius

          // Spacing
          spacing: '1rem',                      // 16px spacing unit
        },
      }}
    >
      {children}
    </ClerkProvider>
  )
}
```

**CSS Variable Names**: All appearance variables are also available as CSS custom properties with the `--clerk-` prefix in kebab-case:
- `colorPrimary` → `--clerk-color-primary`
- `borderRadius` → `--clerk-border-radius`
- `fontFamily` → `--clerk-font-family`

### 3. Using CSS Variables Directly in Stylesheets

**Source**: [Clerk CSS Variables Support](https://clerk.com/changelog/2025-07-15-clerk-css-variables-support)

**Relevance**: As of July 2025, you can now define Clerk variables in your CSS instead of JavaScript, which integrates better with existing design systems.

**Implementation in globals.css**:

```css
/* In your src/app/globals.css */
:root {
  /* Clerk theme variables - Light mode */
  --clerk-color-primary: #000000;
  --clerk-color-foreground: #000000;
  --clerk-color-background: #ffffff;
  --clerk-color-neutral: #71717a;  /* zinc-500 */
  --clerk-border-radius: 0px;
  --clerk-font-family: 'Switzer', -apple-system, sans-serif;
}

.dark {
  /* Dark mode overrides */
  --clerk-color-primary: #ffffff;
  --clerk-color-foreground: #ffffff;
  --clerk-color-background: #000000;
  --clerk-color-neutral: #a1a1aa;  /* zinc-400 */
}
```

This approach automatically syncs with your theme toggle without JavaScript changes.

### 4. Fine-Grained Element Styling

**Source**: [Clerk Elements Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/overview)

**Relevance**: For precise control over specific UI elements like buttons, cards, and inputs.

**Example - Matching Your Blueprint Aesthetic**:

```tsx
<ClerkProvider
  appearance={{
    variables: {
      borderRadius: '0px',
      colorPrimary: '#000000',
    },
    elements: {
      // Main card container
      card: {
        border: '1px solid #000000',
        boxShadow: 'none',
      },

      // Card box (wrapper introduced in Core 2)
      cardBox: {
        boxShadow: 'none',
      },

      // Primary buttons
      formButtonPrimary: {
        backgroundColor: '#000000',
        color: '#ffffff',
        border: '1px solid #000000',
        borderRadius: '0px',
        fontSize: '0.875rem',
        fontWeight: 500,
        transition: 'all 100ms ease',
        '&:hover': {
          backgroundColor: '#18181b', // zinc-900
        },
      },

      // Input fields
      formFieldInput: {
        borderRadius: '0px',
        border: '1px solid #d4d4d8', // zinc-300
        fontSize: '0.875rem',
      },

      // Footer links
      footerActionLink: {
        color: '#000000',
        textDecoration: 'none',
        '&:hover': {
          color: '#52525b', // zinc-600
        },
      },

      // Divider lines
      dividerLine: {
        backgroundColor: '#e4e4e7', // zinc-200
      },
    },
  }}
>
  {children}
</ClerkProvider>
```

**Finding Element Names**: Inspect Clerk components in DevTools and look for class names like `cl-formButtonPrimary`. Remove the `cl-` prefix to use as the key in the `elements` object.

### 5. Available baseTheme Presets

**Source**: [Clerk Themes Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/themes)

**Relevance**: Clerk offers 6 preset themes, but for your custom design, you likely won't use these. However, they can be stacked.

**Available Themes**:
```tsx
import { 
  dark,           // Dark theme
  neobrutalism,   // Sharp, bold design (might be useful!)
  shadesOfPurple, // Purple accent theme
  simple,         // Minimal theme
  shadcn,         // shadcn/ui compatible theme
} from '@clerk/themes'
```

**Neobrutalism Theme** might be interesting for your "Technical Blueprint" aesthetic as it emphasizes sharp corners and bold borders:

```tsx
import { neobrutalism } from '@clerk/themes'

<ClerkProvider
  appearance={{
    baseTheme: neobrutalism,
    variables: {
      colorPrimary: '#000000',
      fontFamily: 'Switzer',
      // Override neobrutalism's border radius if needed
      borderRadius: '0px',
    },
  }}
>
```

**Stacking Themes**: You can combine multiple themes:
```tsx
appearance={{
  baseTheme: [dark, neobrutalism], // Last theme takes precedence on conflicts
}}
```

### 6. Complete Implementation Example for Your Design System

**Recommended Approach - Create a Reusable Theme File**:

```tsx
// src/lib/clerk-theme.ts
import type { Appearance } from '@clerk/types'

export const entourageClerkTheme: Appearance = {
  variables: {
    // Color palette - Black/White/Zinc
    colorPrimary: '#000000',
    colorForeground: '#000000',
    colorBackground: '#ffffff',
    colorNeutral: '#71717a',          // zinc-500
    colorMutedForeground: '#a1a1aa',  // zinc-400

    colorInputBackground: '#ffffff',
    colorInputForeground: '#000000',

    // Accent colors from your design system
    colorDanger: '#f43f5e',    // Rose
    colorSuccess: '#10b981',   // Emerald
    colorWarning: '#f59e0b',   // Amber

    // Typography - Switzer font
    fontFamily: 'var(--font-switzer), -apple-system, sans-serif',
    fontSize: '0.875rem',      // 14px
    fontWeight: {
      normal: 400,
      medium: 500,
      semibold: 600,
      bold: 700,
    },

    // Sharp corners - NO border radius
    borderRadius: '0px',

    // Spacing
    spacing: '1rem',
  },

  elements: {
    // Card container - sharp corners, clean borders
    card: {
      border: '1px solid #000000',
      boxShadow: 'none',
    },

    cardBox: {
      boxShadow: 'none',
    },

    // Primary button - solid black
    formButtonPrimary: {
      backgroundColor: '#000000',
      color: '#ffffff',
      border: '1px solid #000000',
      borderRadius: '0px',
      fontSize: '0.875rem',
      fontWeight: 500,
      textTransform: 'none',
      transition: 'all 100ms ease',

      '&:hover': {
        backgroundColor: '#18181b',
      },

      '&:focus': {
        boxShadow: '0 0 0 2px #000000',
      },
    },

    // Secondary button - outline style
    formButtonSecondary: {
      backgroundColor: 'transparent',
      color: '#000000',
      border: '1px solid #000000',
      borderRadius: '0px',

      '&:hover': {
        backgroundColor: '#fafafa',
      },
    },

    // Input fields
    formFieldInput: {
      borderRadius: '0px',
      border: '1px solid #d4d4d8',
      fontSize: '0.875rem',

      '&:focus': {
        borderColor: '#000000',
        boxShadow: '0 0 0 1px #000000',
      },
    },

    // Footer
    footer: {
      backgroundColor: 'transparent',
      borderTop: '1px solid #e4e4e7',
    },

    footerActionLink: {
      color: '#000000',
      fontSize: '0.875rem',
      textDecoration: 'none',

      '&:hover': {
        color: '#52525b',
      },
    },

    // Dividers
    dividerLine: {
      backgroundColor: '#e4e4e7',
      height: '1px',
    },

    // Social buttons
    socialButtonsBlockButton: {
      borderRadius: '0px',
      border: '1px solid #d4d4d8',

      '&:hover': {
        backgroundColor: '#fafafa',
      },
    },
  },
}

// Dark mode variant
export const entourageClerkThemeDark: Appearance = {
  variables: {
    colorPrimary: '#ffffff',
    colorForeground: '#ffffff',
    colorBackground: '#000000',
    colorNeutral: '#a1a1aa',          // zinc-400
    colorMutedForeground: '#71717a',  // zinc-500

    colorInputBackground: '#000000',
    colorInputForeground: '#ffffff',

    colorDanger: '#f43f5e',
    colorSuccess: '#10b981',
    colorWarning: '#f59e0b',

    fontFamily: 'var(--font-switzer), -apple-system, sans-serif',
    fontSize: '0.875rem',
    borderRadius: '0px',
    spacing: '1rem',
  },

  elements: {
    card: {
      border: '1px solid #ffffff',
      boxShadow: 'none',
    },

    cardBox: {
      boxShadow: 'none',
    },

    formButtonPrimary: {
      backgroundColor: '#ffffff',
      color: '#000000',
      border: '1px solid #ffffff',
      borderRadius: '0px',

      '&:hover': {
        backgroundColor: '#e4e4e7',
      },
    },

    formFieldInput: {
      borderRadius: '0px',
      border: '1px solid #52525b',

      '&:focus': {
        borderColor: '#ffffff',
        boxShadow: '0 0 0 1px #ffffff',
      },
    },

    dividerLine: {
      backgroundColor: '#3f3f46',
    },
  },
}
```

### 7. Integration with Next.js and Theme Toggle

**Dynamic Theme Switching**:

```tsx
// src/app/layout.tsx
'use client'

import { ClerkProvider } from '@clerk/nextjs'
import { useTheme } from 'next-themes'
import { entourageClerkTheme, entourageClerkThemeDark } from '@/lib/clerk-theme'

function ClerkThemeProvider({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const { resolvedTheme } = useTheme()

  return (
    <ClerkProvider
      appearance={resolvedTheme === 'dark' ? entourageClerkThemeDark : entourageClerkTheme}
    >
      {children}
    </ClerkProvider>
  )
}
```

**Or use CSS variables approach** (recommended for automatic sync):

```tsx
// src/app/layout.tsx
import { ClerkProvider } from '@clerk/nextjs'

export default function RootLayout({ children }) {
  return (
    <ClerkProvider
      appearance={{
        variables: {
          borderRadius: '0px',
          fontFamily: 'var(--font-switzer)',
          // Other variables defined in globals.css via --clerk-* CSS vars
        },
      }}
    >
      {children}
    </ClerkProvider>
  )
}
```

### 8. Component-Specific Customization

**Different styling for SignIn vs SignUp**:

```tsx
<ClerkProvider
  appearance={{
    // Global defaults
    variables: { borderRadius: '0px' },

    // Component-specific overrides
    signIn: {
      elements: {
        card: { border: '2px solid #000000' },
      },
    },

    signUp: {
      elements: {
        card: { border: '1px solid #000000' },
      },
    },
  }}
>
```

## Additional Resources

- [Clerk Appearance Prop Overview](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/overview) - Main customization guide
- [Clerk Variables Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/variables) - Complete variable reference
- [Clerk Themes Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/themes) - Preset themes and stacking
- [Clerk CSS Variables Support Changelog](https://clerk.com/changelog/2025-07-15-clerk-css-variables-support) - New CSS variable features (July 2025)
- [Bring Your Own CSS Guide](https://clerk.com/docs/guides/customizing-clerk/appearance-prop/bring-your-own-css) - Advanced CSS customization
- [Clerk Elements](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/elements/guides/styling) - Unstyled components for maximum customization

## Browser Compatibility Note

Clerk's CSS variable system uses modern CSS features (`color-mix()` and relative color syntax) requiring:
- Chrome 111+ (color-mix), 119+ (relative colors)
- Firefox 113+ (color-mix), 120+ (relative colors)
- Safari 16.2+ (color-mix), 16.4+ (relative colors)

For broader support, use static color values like `#000000` instead of CSS variables or color functions.

## Key Takeaways for Your Implementation

1. **Set `borderRadius: '0px'`** in variables - this is critical for sharp corners
2. **Use Switzer font**: `fontFamily: 'var(--font-switzer), -apple-system, sans-serif'`
3. **Black/White/Zinc palette**: Use `#000000`, `#ffffff`, and zinc shades (`#71717a`, `#a1a1aa`, `#d4d4d8`, `#e4e4e7`)
4. **CSS variable approach** (new in 2025) integrates best with your design system
5. **Remove box shadows**: Set `boxShadow: 'none'` on card elements for cleaner look
6. **Consider neobrutalism theme** as a starting point - it has sharp corners by default

Sources:
- [Clerk Appearance Prop Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/overview)
- [Appearance Prop: Variables](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/variables)
- [Appearance Prop: Themes](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/themes)
- [Clerk CSS Variables Support](https://clerk.com/changelog/2025-07-15-clerk-css-variables-support)
- [CSS Variables Support Announcement](https://clerk.com/changelog/2025-07-08-css-variables-support)
- [Bring Your Own CSS](https://clerk.com/docs/guides/customizing-clerk/appearance-prop/bring-your-own-css)
- [Clerk Elements Styling](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/elements/guides/styling)
- [Mastering Clerk Themes](https://www.codingeasypeasy.com/blog/mastering-clerk-themes-customize-your-authentication-ui-with-clerkthemes)

Perfect! Now let me compile a comprehensive guide with concrete code examples for your use case.

## Summary

I've researched Clerk's authentication component customization system. Here's a comprehensive guide to matching Clerk components to your black/white/zinc design system with sharp corners.

## Detailed Findings

### 1. ClerkProvider Appearance Prop Structure

**Source**: [Clerk Appearance Prop Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/overview)

**Relevance**: The `appearance` prop is the main customization interface. It can be applied globally to `<ClerkProvider>` or to individual components like `<SignIn />` and `<SignUp />`.

**Key Structure**:
```tsx
<ClerkProvider
  appearance={{
    baseTheme: undefined,     // Optional preset theme
    variables: {},            // General styles (colors, fonts, spacing)
    elements: {},             // Fine-grained element styling
    layout: {}                // Logo, terms links, etc.
  }}
>
  {children}
</ClerkProvider>
```

### 2. Available CSS Variables for Your Design System

**Source**: [Clerk Variables Prop Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/variables)

**Relevance**: These variables control the core visual properties that define your brand identity.

**Complete Variable List for Black/White/Zinc Theme**:

```tsx
import { ClerkProvider } from '@clerk/nextjs'

export default function RootLayout({ children }) {
  return (
    <ClerkProvider
      appearance={{
        variables: {
          // Colors - Black/White/Zinc palette
          colorPrimary: '#000000',              // Primary actions (black)
          colorForeground: '#000000',           // Primary text (black)
          colorBackground: '#ffffff',           // Card background (white)
          colorNeutral: '#71717a',              // Zinc-500 for neutral elements
          colorMutedForeground: '#a1a1aa',      // Zinc-400 for muted text

          // Input fields
          colorInputBackground: '#ffffff',      // White input backgrounds
          colorInputForeground: '#000000',      // Black input text

          // State colors (can use your accent palette)
          colorDanger: '#f43f5e',               // Rose for errors
          colorSuccess: '#10b981',              // Emerald for success
          colorWarning: '#f59e0b',              // Amber for warnings

          // Typography
          fontFamily: 'Switzer, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, sans-serif',
          fontSize: '0.875rem',                 // 14px base
          fontWeight: {
            normal: 400,
            medium: 500,
            semibold: 600,
            bold: 700,
          },

          // Sharp corners - CRITICAL for your design
          borderRadius: '0px',                  // NO border radius

          // Spacing
          spacing: '1rem',                      // 16px spacing unit
        },
      }}
    >
      {children}
    </ClerkProvider>
  )
}
```

**CSS Variable Names**: All appearance variables are also available as CSS custom properties with the `--clerk-` prefix in kebab-case:
- `colorPrimary` → `--clerk-color-primary`
- `borderRadius` → `--clerk-border-radius`
- `fontFamily` → `--clerk-font-family`

### 3. Using CSS Variables Directly in Stylesheets

**Source**: [Clerk CSS Variables Support](https://clerk.com/changelog/2025-07-15-clerk-css-variables-support)

**Relevance**: As of July 2025, you can now define Clerk variables in your CSS instead of JavaScript, which integrates better with existing design systems.

**Implementation in globals.css**:

```css
/* In your src/app/globals.css */
:root {
  /* Clerk theme variables - Light mode */
  --clerk-color-primary: #000000;
  --clerk-color-foreground: #000000;
  --clerk-color-background: #ffffff;
  --clerk-color-neutral: #71717a;  /* zinc-500 */
  --clerk-border-radius: 0px;
  --clerk-font-family: 'Switzer', -apple-system, sans-serif;
}

.dark {
  /* Dark mode overrides */
  --clerk-color-primary: #ffffff;
  --clerk-color-foreground: #ffffff;
  --clerk-color-background: #000000;
  --clerk-color-neutral: #a1a1aa;  /* zinc-400 */
}
```

This approach automatically syncs with your theme toggle without JavaScript changes.

### 4. Fine-Grained Element Styling

**Source**: [Clerk Elements Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/overview)

**Relevance**: For precise control over specific UI elements like buttons, cards, and inputs.

**Example - Matching Your Blueprint Aesthetic**:

```tsx
<ClerkProvider
  appearance={{
    variables: {
      borderRadius: '0px',
      colorPrimary: '#000000',
    },
    elements: {
      // Main card container
      card: {
        border: '1px solid #000000',
        boxShadow: 'none',
      },

      // Card box (wrapper introduced in Core 2)
      cardBox: {
        boxShadow: 'none',
      },

      // Primary buttons
      formButtonPrimary: {
        backgroundColor: '#000000',
        color: '#ffffff',
        border: '1px solid #000000',
        borderRadius: '0px',
        fontSize: '0.875rem',
        fontWeight: 500,
        transition: 'all 100ms ease',
        '&:hover': {
          backgroundColor: '#18181b', // zinc-900
        },
      },

      // Input fields
      formFieldInput: {
        borderRadius: '0px',
        border: '1px solid #d4d4d8', // zinc-300
        fontSize: '0.875rem',
      },

      // Footer links
      footerActionLink: {
        color: '#000000',
        textDecoration: 'none',
        '&:hover': {
          color: '#52525b', // zinc-600
        },
      },

      // Divider lines
      dividerLine: {
        backgroundColor: '#e4e4e7', // zinc-200
      },
    },
  }}
>
  {children}
</ClerkProvider>
```

**Finding Element Names**: Inspect Clerk components in DevTools and look for class names like `cl-formButtonPrimary`. Remove the `cl-` prefix to use as the key in the `elements` object.

### 5. Available baseTheme Presets

**Source**: [Clerk Themes Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/themes)

**Relevance**: Clerk offers 6 preset themes, but for your custom design, you likely won't use these. However, they can be stacked.

**Available Themes**:
```tsx
import { 
  dark,           // Dark theme
  neobrutalism,   // Sharp, bold design (might be useful!)
  shadesOfPurple, // Purple accent theme
  simple,         // Minimal theme
  shadcn,         // shadcn/ui compatible theme
} from '@clerk/themes'
```

**Neobrutalism Theme** might be interesting for your "Technical Blueprint" aesthetic as it emphasizes sharp corners and bold borders:

```tsx
import { neobrutalism } from '@clerk/themes'

<ClerkProvider
  appearance={{
    baseTheme: neobrutalism,
    variables: {
      colorPrimary: '#000000',
      fontFamily: 'Switzer',
      // Override neobrutalism's border radius if needed
      borderRadius: '0px',
    },
  }}
>
```

**Stacking Themes**: You can combine multiple themes:
```tsx
appearance={{
  baseTheme: [dark, neobrutalism], // Last theme takes precedence on conflicts
}}
```

### 6. Complete Implementation Example for Your Design System

**Recommended Approach - Create a Reusable Theme File**:

```tsx
// src/lib/clerk-theme.ts
import type { Appearance } from '@clerk/types'

export const entourageClerkTheme: Appearance = {
  variables: {
    // Color palette - Black/White/Zinc
    colorPrimary: '#000000',
    colorForeground: '#000000',
    colorBackground: '#ffffff',
    colorNeutral: '#71717a',          // zinc-500
    colorMutedForeground: '#a1a1aa',  // zinc-400

    colorInputBackground: '#ffffff',
    colorInputForeground: '#000000',

    // Accent colors from your design system
    colorDanger: '#f43f5e',    // Rose
    colorSuccess: '#10b981',   // Emerald
    colorWarning: '#f59e0b',   // Amber

    // Typography - Switzer font
    fontFamily: 'var(--font-switzer), -apple-system, sans-serif',
    fontSize: '0.875rem',      // 14px
    fontWeight: {
      normal: 400,
      medium: 500,
      semibold: 600,
      bold: 700,
    },

    // Sharp corners - NO border radius
    borderRadius: '0px',

    // Spacing
    spacing: '1rem',
  },

  elements: {
    // Card container - sharp corners, clean borders
    card: {
      border: '1px solid #000000',
      boxShadow: 'none',
    },

    cardBox: {
      boxShadow: 'none',
    },

    // Primary button - solid black
    formButtonPrimary: {
      backgroundColor: '#000000',
      color: '#ffffff',
      border: '1px solid #000000',
      borderRadius: '0px',
      fontSize: '0.875rem',
      fontWeight: 500,
      textTransform: 'none',
      transition: 'all 100ms ease',

      '&:hover': {
        backgroundColor: '#18181b',
      },

      '&:focus': {
        boxShadow: '0 0 0 2px #000000',
      },
    },

    // Secondary button - outline style
    formButtonSecondary: {
      backgroundColor: 'transparent',
      color: '#000000',
      border: '1px solid #000000',
      borderRadius: '0px',

      '&:hover': {
        backgroundColor: '#fafafa',
      },
    },

    // Input fields
    formFieldInput: {
      borderRadius: '0px',
      border: '1px solid #d4d4d8',
      fontSize: '0.875rem',

      '&:focus': {
        borderColor: '#000000',
        boxShadow: '0 0 0 1px #000000',
      },
    },

    // Footer
    footer: {
      backgroundColor: 'transparent',
      borderTop: '1px solid #e4e4e7',
    },

    footerActionLink: {
      color: '#000000',
      fontSize: '0.875rem',
      textDecoration: 'none',

      '&:hover': {
        color: '#52525b',
      },
    },

    // Dividers
    dividerLine: {
      backgroundColor: '#e4e4e7',
      height: '1px',
    },

    // Social buttons
    socialButtonsBlockButton: {
      borderRadius: '0px',
      border: '1px solid #d4d4d8',

      '&:hover': {
        backgroundColor: '#fafafa',
      },
    },
  },
}

// Dark mode variant
export const entourageClerkThemeDark: Appearance = {
  variables: {
    colorPrimary: '#ffffff',
    colorForeground: '#ffffff',
    colorBackground: '#000000',
    colorNeutral: '#a1a1aa',          // zinc-400
    colorMutedForeground: '#71717a',  // zinc-500

    colorInputBackground: '#000000',
    colorInputForeground: '#ffffff',

    colorDanger: '#f43f5e',
    colorSuccess: '#10b981',
    colorWarning: '#f59e0b',

    fontFamily: 'var(--font-switzer), -apple-system, sans-serif',
    fontSize: '0.875rem',
    borderRadius: '0px',
    spacing: '1rem',
  },

  elements: {
    card: {
      border: '1px solid #ffffff',
      boxShadow: 'none',
    },

    cardBox: {
      boxShadow: 'none',
    },

    formButtonPrimary: {
      backgroundColor: '#ffffff',
      color: '#000000',
      border: '1px solid #ffffff',
      borderRadius: '0px',

      '&:hover': {
        backgroundColor: '#e4e4e7',
      },
    },

    formFieldInput: {
      borderRadius: '0px',
      border: '1px solid #52525b',

      '&:focus': {
        borderColor: '#ffffff',
        boxShadow: '0 0 0 1px #ffffff',
      },
    },

    dividerLine: {
      backgroundColor: '#3f3f46',
    },
  },
}
```

### 7. Integration with Next.js and Theme Toggle

**Dynamic Theme Switching**:

```tsx
// src/app/layout.tsx
'use client'

import { ClerkProvider } from '@clerk/nextjs'
import { useTheme } from 'next-themes'
import { entourageClerkTheme, entourageClerkThemeDark } from '@/lib/clerk-theme'

function ClerkThemeProvider({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const { resolvedTheme } = useTheme()

  return (
    <ClerkProvider
      appearance={resolvedTheme === 'dark' ? entourageClerkThemeDark : entourageClerkTheme}
    >
      {children}
    </ClerkProvider>
  )
}
```

**Or use CSS variables approach** (recommended for automatic sync):

```tsx
// src/app/layout.tsx
import { ClerkProvider } from '@clerk/nextjs'

export default function RootLayout({ children }) {
  return (
    <ClerkProvider
      appearance={{
        variables: {
          borderRadius: '0px',
          fontFamily: 'var(--font-switzer)',
          // Other variables defined in globals.css via --clerk-* CSS vars
        },
      }}
    >
      {children}
    </ClerkProvider>
  )
}
```

### 8. Component-Specific Customization

**Different styling for SignIn vs SignUp**:

```tsx
<ClerkProvider
  appearance={{
    // Global defaults
    variables: { borderRadius: '0px' },

    // Component-specific overrides
    signIn: {
      elements: {
        card: { border: '2px solid #000000' },
      },
    },

    signUp: {
      elements: {
        card: { border: '1px solid #000000' },
      },
    },
  }}
>
```

## Additional Resources

- [Clerk Appearance Prop Overview](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/overview) - Main customization guide
- [Clerk Variables Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/variables) - Complete variable reference
- [Clerk Themes Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/themes) - Preset themes and stacking
- [Clerk CSS Variables Support Changelog](https://clerk.com/changelog/2025-07-15-clerk-css-variables-support) - New CSS variable features (July 2025)
- [Bring Your Own CSS Guide](https://clerk.com/docs/guides/customizing-clerk/appearance-prop/bring-your-own-css) - Advanced CSS customization
- [Clerk Elements](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/elements/guides/styling) - Unstyled components for maximum customization

## Browser Compatibility Note

Clerk's CSS variable system uses modern CSS features (`color-mix()` and relative color syntax) requiring:
- Chrome 111+ (color-mix), 119+ (relative colors)
- Firefox 113+ (color-mix), 120+ (relative colors)
- Safari 16.2+ (color-mix), 16.4+ (relative colors)

For broader support, use static color values like `#000000` instead of CSS variables or color functions.

## Key Takeaways for Your Implementation

1. **Set `borderRadius: '0px'`** in variables - this is critical for sharp corners
2. **Use Switzer font**: `fontFamily: 'var(--font-switzer), -apple-system, sans-serif'`
3. **Black/White/Zinc palette**: Use `#000000`, `#ffffff`, and zinc shades (`#71717a`, `#a1a1aa`, `#d4d4d8`, `#e4e4e7`)
4. **CSS variable approach** (new in 2025) integrates best with your design system
5. **Remove box shadows**: Set `boxShadow: 'none'` on card elements for cleaner look
6. **Consider neobrutalism theme** as a starting point - it has sharp corners by default

Sources:
- [Clerk Appearance Prop Documentation](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/overview)
- [Appearance Prop: Variables](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/variables)
- [Appearance Prop: Themes](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/themes)
- [Clerk CSS Variables Support](https://clerk.com/changelog/2025-07-15-clerk-css-variables-support)
- [CSS Variables Support Announcement](https://clerk.com/changelog/2025-07-08-css-variables-support)
- [Bring Your Own CSS](https://clerk.com/docs/guides/customizing-clerk/appearance-prop/bring-your-own-css)
- [Clerk Elements Styling](https://clerk.com/docs/customization/elements/guides/styling)
- [Mastering Clerk Themes](https://www.codingeasypeasy.com/blog/mastering-clerk-themes-customize-your-authentication-ui-with-clerkthemes)

